I’d never had the opportunity to photograph a wedding @fonthillcastleweddings before. I sure hope I get to do more. It’s a stunning place, and there are so many photographic opportunities. Laura and Barrett braved torrential rain during their ceremony, and while we all got soaked, it was all worth it. 

All images captured with Nikon Z9 or Z 6II

I’ve been working with this wonderful family for nearly 2 years. This past Saturday, Stephanie and Brad celebrated their day at the picturesque @libertyhouserestaurant, with mind blowing views of the Manhattan skyline across the Hudson in Jersey City, NJ. Here, Stephanie saw her dad for the first time after she was ready, and the emotions flowed throughout the room. On the technical side, my Nikon Z9 locked on to the eyes of her father, and it didn’t let go. In the past, it wasn’t always easy to focus directly into such overpowering backlighting. This camera just keeps getting better with each update, and it’s really changed the way I’m able to shoot. Composition, light, and the moment are all I really need to think about these days. It’s pretty damn liberating. 

Nikon Z 9, FTZ II, Nikkor 105 F1.4E ED
1/640th f/2.0 @ ISO 1600

This image is from a recent branding session for Jeanne Ruddy, an incredibly accomplished dancer, teacher, and founder of the Performance Garage in Philadelphia. Jeanne is a former principal dancer with the Martha Graham company, and was a faculty member at Juilliard for a decade. The Performance Garage is an impressive, intimate, 100 seat theater dedicated to supporting dance artists, companies, educators and choreographers. I had a blast working in her space, and I would love to see a performance there. Here’s one from the lobby area.

Nikon Z 9, Nikkor Z 24-70mm F2.8S

It’s not hard to see why people love getting married @libertyhouserestaurant in Jersey City NJ. The view, both daytime and evening, is breathtaking. Photographically, choosing the correct focal length is important since my intent was to make it appear as though the skyline is right behind them. Balancing the intensity of light on my subject with the city lights was easy with my @stellaprolights CLX 10, and the camera easily found the eyes, even in a lower lighting scenario. The rest was easy with Stephanie and Bradley.

Photo geek post... The Nikkor 85mm f/1.4, both the D and G versions, were my favorite portrait lenses for many, many years. In 2016, Nikon introduced the Nikkor 105 f/1.4 E ED. It quickly became my lens of choice for so many things- no matter the assignment. It’s the best lens I’ve ever used. It produced a look I couldn’t achieve with any other piece of glass I had, and continues to be my workhorse for so many applications. Enter the new Nikkor Z 85mm f/1.2S that is now in development. While I haven’t had the chance to get my hands on it, I can’t wait to see how it performs, and whether it’ll make the 105 jealous :-) The Z system just keeps getting better! This image of Allison, a bride who was married @pleasetouchmuseum, was created back in 2011 with My D3S and the 85 f/1.4G. Oh, and don’t ya love birdcage veils? 

Nikon D3S Nikkor 85mm f/1.4G
1/320 f.1.4 @ ISO 500

On this frigid, east coast Monday, I’m working on my website, cleaning up some bad links, and adding some new images and venues. I came across this image from “One Atlantic”, which closed last year in Atlantic City. While my fellow wedding pros will recall the grueling walk to the end of the pier, I’ll also point out that I enjoyed the views of the ocean, and the extremely friendly staff who ran the place. I was sorry to see it go. This image was taken immediately after a ceremony while the couple was taking a few minutes to reflect. The seconds after a ceremony can yield some killer moments. I followed them out of the room and into this one, but made sure to keep my distance with my 70-200 in order to maintain some privacy for them. I really doubt I’d have made this image had I been in their face with a short lens. I got lucky when Jessica showed Keith her new piece of hardware on her finger. While I won’t miss that long walk on the long pier, I will miss the gelato in Caesars when we were finished shooting!

Nikon D4, Nikkor 70-200 f/2.8 VRIIG
1/320th f/2.8 @ ISO 640

January isn’t the busiest time of year for weddings in this part of the world, so I do my best to keep my site fresh and do some other things to pretend I’m being productive 😊. While curating images, I looked at the metadata and was floored that it's 15 years old. I made this in February of ’08 during their wedding @bellevuehotelphilly. It was a bitter cold day, yet they were still enthusiastic about making some photographs outside. Sometimes, while driving my couples around for portraits, I’ll see some light I feel compelled to use. The sun was setting along Kelly Drive in Philadelphia and I literally pulled off the road and onto the walkway because the light was so sweet. This is a wonderful example of what warm, luscious, directional light can provide. We were back in the car in less than 2 minutes and worked our way back to the Bellevue. My main goal is to create images that are timeless, rather than trendy. This one gets to stay on the site.

Nikon D3 Nikkor 70-200 F2.8 VR
1/1000th F2.8 @ ISO 160

I’ve been doing a ton of headshots in the studio. I have a few different set ups depending upon the needs of the client. With actors/performers, or more when I need a more creative approach, I’ll do some different things to allow their personalities to shine. But, for a basic, high key, corporate portrait, this is one method I’ve been using. It’s quick, simple, and looks great. I use 2 @stellaprolights CLX 10’s to illuminate the white seamless. I’ll use another CLX 8 or 10 into a deep @profoto umbrella. I’ll also use a @vflatworld for some nice fill. It’s quick, simple, and I get good results. Nothing will replace my @profoto lights as my main studio tools, but if I’m doing a quick, down and dirty headshot, this is really effective. Here’s a BTS, and then swipe for the result.

Headshot captured with:
Nikon Z 9, Nikkor 105mm f/1.4E ED w FTZII
1/640th f/2 @ ISO 1000

Here’s a little recap from last week in Vegas! @wppievents is back, and if this year was an indication of the future of this organization, it’s really encouraging. A packed trade show, photographers hungry for education, innovative products, and networking you simply can’t find anywhere else in this industry. @nikonusa has allowed me the privilege of speaking on their behalf since 2005. I’ve never been more grateful to represent their brand, and to be part of the Nikon family. corradophotography knocked it out of the park with a line up of gifted speakers from across the Americas. One of the many highlights was my participation in the Nikon Shootout. The idea behind the shootout was to have 4 different photographers photograph the lovely model, @journeetoda, in the same conditions. Each photographer had 10 minutes, and the results were stunning. It was a blast sharing the event with @cloeramirezphoto, @kanayo_adibe, and my old friend, @johnmichaelcooper. Huge thanks to @jerryghionis for always being an entertaining MC. Shout out to @westcottlighting and @stellaprolights for loaning us some gear for that evening. Here’s a few images from my 7 talks in 3 days. HUGE thank you to @crissyeverhartphoto for the BTS images.

Last week, @wppievents in Vegas, I presented a @nikonusa talk on how my approach and workflow has changed on a wedding day. In the past, I’ve been a single point focus photographer- taking the time to focus on a single point in the frame after composing the image. When shooting at a shallow depth of field, there's less room for error with your focusing technique. On the Nikon trade show stage, I demonstrated how the Nikon Z 9 locks on to the eye- even when only the subject’s profile is in view- and all I need to concentrate on is my composition and the moment itself. It’s pretty darn liberating when you simply know an image will be sharp every single time. It also allows me the opportunity to use the entire frame for more interesting compositions. Big thanks to Teddy, a recent groom, for being a great subject. 

Nikon Z 9 Nikkor Z 70-200 f/2.8S
1/640th f/2.8 @ ISO 1600

Setting the stage for moments, without staging the moments. That’s kind of how I approach wedding preparation. No, this isn’t photojournalism. It’s wedding photography. There are plenty of images throughout a wedding day where I’m a purist, and I’ll allow photos to unfold without any prompting or direction whatsoever. That said, I don’t need to adhere to those PJ standards for images like this. By simply asking the flower girls to go and play around with the gown, they engaged in a way that allows me to include them in the moment. I chose the light and compositional scenario, but the rest is “fairly” organic. Also, how beautiful @fonthillcastleweddings? I can’t wait to work there again!

Nikon Z 9 Nikkor 105 f/1.4E ED
1/500th f.1/6 @ ISO 1000

Over the past 15-20 years, one of my favorite areas to create images has been City Hall in Philadelphia. The directional light created by the enormous archways combined with the rustic, textured walls of this majestic structure have provided me with a place to create portraits for hundreds of different types of clients over the years. I’ve photographed ad campaigns, weddings, engagement sessions, Mitzvah portraits, etc, and the light never ceases to amaze me. 

Within the atrium of this amazing building, my workshop students have grasped the concept of directional light, juxtaposition of shadows and highlights, and they’ve learned how that promotes drama in their images. Rain, sunshine, snow, sleet… the light pours in before dark. In this image, I added a little kicker from my @stellaprolights CLX 10 and giving Matthew a little fill- since the light coming from the archway was only striking Victoria. All of that said, the real impact of the image is all about the lovely chemistry and interaction of this beautiful couple. After all, as I’ve said many times, we’re only as good as our clients. 

Nikon Z 9, Nikkor Z 70-200 f/2.8S
1/1600th f/2.8 @ ISO 1600

Here’s one from a recent wedding with my new Nikon Z 8. After Michelle was dressed and ready, we made our way up to the 33rd floor of the @loewsphiladelphia for some portraits with a spectacular view of our city. Michelle was pretty terrific to work with, and she was incredibly comfortable in front of the camera. 

Relying upon the accuracy of the Z 8’s electronic viewfinder, I chose the desired exposure balance between subject and background quickly. I wanted to compress my subject with my background, so I moved quite a way back from her and into another room so I could rack out my lens to 200mm to get the look I’d envisioned. I’ve been using the Z 8’s 3D tracking, which is unique to the Z 9 and Z 8. Focusing has never been this easy, or this accurate. 

Nikkor 70-200mm f/2.8S

It’s not every day I get an opportunity to create portraits at the very top of the Capitol dome in Washington DC. I’ll be photographing Elyce and Steven’s DC wedding in September, and we were given the privilege of photographing them atop the dome thanks to Steven’s connections. It’s not an easy ascent, however. We had to climb 300 steps between the inner and outer shells of the Capitol- an interstitial space- in order to obtain access to the observation balcony beneath the Statue of Freedom. I had to pack light due to the incredibly narrow passage. I selected my Nikon Z 9 and my Nikon 14-30 f/4S lens, and also had my Nikkor 70-200 f2/8S for some views of DC once atop the balcony…. Pretty cool day. 

Nikon Z 9, Nikkor 14-30 f/4S

A few more images after finishing up a project for Huntingdon Valley County Club. I’m truly hoping to have the opportunity to capture other incredible golf courses in the @gaofphilly. HVCC opened in 1897, and it’s incredibly rich in history. My hope is that I captured the course in a way that would make the architects, William Flynn and Howard Toomey smile. I appreciate the opportunity to spend some time out there over the past few weeks. 

A little about my approach to the assignment… In stating the obvious, the light is the most critical element, by far. I made several trips in order to get a sense of what holes would have the most desirable light in the early am, or pm. While it sounds simple, the Canadian wild fires threw a huge wrench into my plans. Flat, hazy light just doesn’t work for a golf course. I wanted clean, contrasty light in order to show contours of the topography. In addition, soot filled skies just don’t work :-) After multiple trips both early and late, my patience paid off with the light I needed. I’m so used to working quickly with wedding and portrait clients. This type of work required me to really slow down and observe. I also had to think like a golfer, not just a photographer. I did my best to be mindful of the course design, highlighting elements that these brilliant architects/artists would want featured. I hope my work did their work some justice. I can’t wait to make some enormous prints. The 45MP from my Nikon Z 8 will allow me to go pretty large. But, along with the native resolution of the camera, some of the scenes called for multiple frames stitched together which produced a few images that are about 25,000 pixels on the long side, so they’ll allow me to make HUGE images. Fun stuff. More tk. 

All images with Nikon Z 8 and Nikkor S lenses. 
Some made with a Tiffen graduated ND filter.

I had the privilege of photographing Landon’s parent’s wedding back in 2004. A few months ago, I photographed Landon’s Bar Mitzvah. In addition to the “typical” mitzvah photos- child wearing tallit on bima, rabbi with the child in front of the ark, child reading from the torah…. Etc, my goal is to learn something about that kid. Who are they? What do they love at that age? What passions do they have? I’ve captured kids in dance studios, theaters, football fields, and a slew of other settings that places that young person in their element. Landon plays on a traveling basketball team, and he his mitzvah had a Philadelphia 76er theme- something I am totally on board with :-) I spent a little time last night shooting some hoops with my rusty jumper, and captured a real player, Landon, practicing on his driveway. 

A little photo info- When I photographed sports for the Philadelphia Inquirer, I used manual focus. That was a learned skillset, to be sure. I rarely have sports assignments anymore, but being able to capture nearly 100% of my images in focus isn’t something I recall doing with my F3 :-) I simply used the 3D tracking with my Nikon Z 8, controlled my background and composition, and let Landon and my camera do the hard work. 

Nikon Z 8, Nikkor 85mm F1.2
1/3200th f/1.2 @ ISO 250

This is the look of pure joy. This wedding was a special one for me. I’ve known Luca for 15 years. He was one of my first models for my Lighting and Skillset Bootcamp that began in late 2007. Our friendship developed over the years, and we’d chat here and there. I’ve seen him grow from a nutty, absent minded college kid into the mature, conscientious, warm, caring man he’s become. 

A few years ago, Luca called me to ask if I’d be willing to come to his home for a Christmas dinner to take a few pictures of his family. But, I learned it wasn’t just another dinner. Both of his incredible parents were suffering from terminal illnesses, and it was going to be the last Christmas dinner this family would have with their parents. The responsibility wasn’t taken lightly. I had my daughter Samantha with me, and she was able to witness what her father was doing, and the importance of that shoot. I’m still grateful for that. They remain some of the most important images I’ve ever captured. 

All that said, I had the privilege of photographing his wedding this past Sunday. They made me feel like part of the family. I’m so happy for Luca and his beautiful bride, Samantha. 

A little photo info-The Nikkor 85mm f/1.2 is allowing me to do things I haven’t really done in the past. Only the candles lit this image. These moments at a wedding are critical, and having complete confidence that I’ll obtain sharpness in these conditions can’t be overstated. I made a few frames with OCF from this scenario, but it doesn’t come close to the feel of what it looked like with the naked eye. 

Nikon Z 8, NIKKOR 85mm 1/160th f/1.2 @ ISO 4000

Deliz came to me for a branding session. She’s in the “hair” business. Extensions, and other elements that provide amazing style for South Asian, Hispanic, and African American women. We had a blast in the studio with different outfits and lighting schemes, but the goal was, of course, to highlight her hair. It was a 3 light set that combined flash and continuous. The main light was from my Westcott FJ 200 with the grid, another FJ w/grid for the hair light, and then my Light and Motion Stella Pro CLX 10 with a tungsten head shooting through a “cookie” gobo on the background. Controlling spill is critical here. Using grids and scrims in order to prevent spill was critical, and I used a bit of extra power on the hair light to bring out those highlights. Fun stuff! I wish Deliz luck with her hair biz, and hope these images help!

Nikon Z 8, NIKKOR 85mm f/1.2S
1/320th f/1.2 @ ISO 800

Rhetorical question… is there anything better for a photographer than the light in the fall here in the Northeast? It’s warm, clean, crisp, saturated, and the direction is always easily embraced. Here’s one from this past weekend with Jackie and Kevin, who were married @ridgeland.mansion, in Fairmount Park, Philadelphia. The venue is a few seconds from the iconic Belmont Plateau, which provides one of the very best views of the city skyline. Aside from the gorgeous light on Jackie, it’s important to choose a lens that compresses the background in order to make the city a prominent compositional element, and provide context to the location. As an aside, I’m incredibly proud to say that Jackie is the 2nd of 3 siblings in this family whose wedding I’ve documented, and I’ll complete the trifecta in the spring! It’s truly a privilege to work with these people. I’ll share a bunch more from this wedding soon.

This past weekend, I had the privilege of photographing Aasta and Miguel’s wedding @frontandpalmer in Philadelphia. We had a sensational fall day, and had the opportunity to find some great light in some stunning locations where the fall foliage was still pretty amazing. Aasta, a truly exquisite bride, was an absolute blast to photograph. 

Photographically speaking, my lens choice here was my NIKKOR 85mm f/1.2 S. Before I had this in my kit, my favorite lens was my 105 1/4E ED. While still an incredible lens, I was told by my brother and fearless Nikon Ambassador leader, @corradophotography that once I began using this new 85, I’d fall in love with it, and the 105 would get jealous. I didn’t believe him until I saw it for myself. The bokeh(the area out of focus) is even more stunning with the saturated colors of the Philly fall foliage. More to share from this soon. Thanks, Mikey. The 85 is my new axe.

When photographing a portrait session, I’ll often ask myself “why look past the simple, when it simply works?”. For Jackie, simplicity worked well, and it was hard to take a bad portrait of her! After all of the family and bridal portraits were completed, the light was screaming for us to do a few more. I asked her if we could just take another few moments to take advantage of the light, and those moments really added to the day’s take. I’ve been loving the look of my NIKKOR 85mm f/1.2 lately, and it’s been my go-to lens. I just used the backlight from the setting sun, and a little @stellaprolights CLX 10 with the fresnel for a bit of fill. It was a fun day @ridgeland.mansion!

Last week, I had a client ask to purchase files from 13 years ago. Fortunately, my studio managers were extremely organized, and I easily located the drive the files were stored on. As I’ve been known to do, I fell into one of my ADD rabbit holes and have been perusing some of the assignments from 13 years ago, and beyond. It’s pretty interesting to look at work from years ago. Lots of criticism, second guessing, and perhaps even a few laughs at some of the choices I made. But there were still a few frames I’d be happy to share. I’m not sure why I’ve sort of gone away from sitting a bride down for a quick portrait to start the day, but I need to go back to it now that I have my NIKKOR 85mm f/1.2 in the bag. This is the lovely Allison, from more than 13 years ago.

Whenever I see a dramatic sky while photographing a portrait session, I’ll do my best to try and find lower ground in order to place the sky behind my clients. The most important elements in the frame is the interaction and gesture from this couple. The image is nothing without their body positioning and the way they relate to one another. The weather took a bit of a turn, and the skies became pretty ominous before their ceremony @mountaincreek resort in Vernon NJ. Luca and Samantha were at the top of the resort waiting for their guests to arrive, and I simply found my way down the slope, had them dance around, and I exposed for the threatening sky behind them. A long lens to compress the scene was also imperative to bring the sky closer to the subjects. It was one of my favorite weddings of the year.

When I first began photographing South Asian weddings 20 years ago or so, I had to react to, rather than anticipate the moments at these stunning events because I had so much to learn about all of the various symbolic elements. I’m still learning things at each event, but I’ve acquired a ton of knowledge about so many unique customs over the years. 
Here, during a “Ring Rasam” game - a fun ritual where a ring is hidden deep inside a bowl filled with various things, Siva and Sophia battle to find the ring to see who’ll rule the roost at home. This was a blast to capture.
